        <h1>South Sudan war survivor tells of horror in Owens talk </h1> 
        <h2>‘Lost boy’ refugee finds success in U.S. </h2> 
        <div class="storybyline">
         <b>BY RONEISHA MULLIN<br>BLADE STAFF WRITER</b>
        </div> 
        <div class="storyicons"> 
         <div class="pw-widget" pw:image="http://www.toledoblade.com/image/2015/02/25/800x_cCM_cT/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-john-dau.jpg"> 
          <a class="pw-button-facebook pw-look-native"></a> 
          <a class="pw-button-twitter pw-look-native"></a> 
          <a class="pw-button-googleplus pw-look-native"></a> 
          <a class="pw-button-reddit pw-look-native"></a> 
          <a class="pw-button-digg pw-look-native"></a> 
          <a class="pw-button-pinterest pw-look-native"></a> 
          <a class="pw-button-email pw-look-native"></a> 
          <a class="pw-button-post pw-look-native"></a> 
         </div> 
         <script src="http://i.po.st/share/script/post-widget.js#publisherKey=6fudh8lupugsvu5vnipv" type="text/javascript"></script> 
        </div> 
       </header> 
       <link rel="image_src" href="http://www.toledoblade.com/image/2015/02/25/100x_b1_cC_z_cT/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-john-dau.jpg"> 
       <div class="storyimage "> 
        <a href="/image/2015/02/25/800x_b1_cCM_z_cT/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-john-dau.jpg" rel="storyimage" class="colorbox" title="Motivational speaker and genocide survivor John Dau speaks at Owens Community College THE BLADE/LORI KING"> 
         <!-- The class colorbox matches the class used in the document.ready function --> <img border="0" src="/image/2015/02/25/300x_b1_a4-3_cCM_z_cT/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-john-dau.jpg" align="left" alt="Motivational speaker and genocide survivor John Dau speaks at Owens Community College" title="WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-john-dau.jpg"> </a> Motivational speaker and genocide survivor John Dau speaks at Owens Community College
        <br> 
        <i>THE BLADE/LORI KING</i> 
        <span class="right innertube blacktext tinytext bold"> <a href="/image/2015/02/25/800x_b1_cCM_z_cT/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-john-dau.jpg" rel="storyimage2" class="colorbox" title="Motivational speaker and genocide survivor John Dau speaks at Owens Community College THE BLADE/LORI KING">Enlarge</a> | <a href="http://toledoblade.mycapture.com/mycapture/remoteimage.asp?image=http%3A//www.toledoblade.com/image/2015/02/25/600x600_cCM_w1_cT/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-john-dau.jpg&amp;Caption=Motivational%20speaker%20and%20genocide%20survivor%20John%20Dau%20speaks%20at%20Owens%20Community%20College&amp;BackText=Return%20to%20the%20Story&amp;backurl=http%3A//www.toledoblade.com/Our-Town-Home-Perrysburg/2015/02/25/South-Sudan-war-survivor-tells-of-horror-in-Owens-talk.html&amp;PhotographerID=8900" target="_blank"> Buy This Photo </a> </span> 
       </div> 
       <p>John Dau and his brothers were asleep when the sounds of whistling bullets and booming bombs ripped through their village in South Sudan in 1987.</p> 
       <p>It was the start of the Second Sudanese Civil War. Sounds of rapid gunfire filled the air, houses were burned down, women and girls abducted, and men killed. Almost 30 years have passed, since that night, but Mr. Dau, who was 13 at the time, can still hear the sounds.</p> 
       <p>“Still, today, I know that sound. I know what it is when I hear it,” Mr. Dau said, speaking Tuesday at Owens Community College. “We were just civilians not opposing anyone that day that terrible work was done.”</p> 
       <p>Students, faculty, and the public filled the seats and lined the walls of the Owens’ Center for Fine and Performing Arts Center in Perrysburg Township to hear the story of Mr. Dau, one of 27,000 “Lost Boys,” who were driven from their villages when the northern African government attacked the ethnic minority population of South Sudan in 1987.</p> 
       <p>Mr. Dau spoke at Owens’ Findlay campus Tuesday morning. Instructors and faculty members from all over the college have been tying Mr. Dau’s story and South Sudan into their classes and students have been studying topics related to his talk.</p> 
       <p>“John's life story is an inspiration,” said Scott Deaner, Owens assistant professor of geography and co-chair of social and behavioral sciences. “Everyone has struggles at some point in life, but hearing what John has gone through and how he's persevered, succeeded, and is working to create better world should be an inspiration for how everyone, no matter what their background or situation, can work to build a better community.”</p> 
       <p>As a teenager, Mr. Dau led groups of displaced boys across Sudan to neighboring Ethiopia and later to a refugee camp in Kenya. Many of them died from starvation, violence, animal attacks and disease. Only 12,000 remained by the time they’d reached Kenya.</p> 
       <link rel="image_src" href="http://www.toledoblade.com/image/2015/02/25/100x_b1_cC_z/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-crowd.jpg"> 
       <div class="storyimage right"> 
        <a href="/image/2015/02/25/800x_b1_cCM_z/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-crowd.jpg" rel="storyimage" class="colorbox" title="Students pack into the FCPA Theatre at Owens Community College for a standing only crowd for Mr. Dau. THE BLADE/LORI KING"> 
         <!-- The class colorbox matches the class used in the document.ready function --> <img border="0" src="/image/2015/02/25/300x_b1_a4-3_cCM_z/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-crowd.jpg" align="left" alt="Students pack into the FCPA Theatre at Owens Community College for a standing only crowd for Mr. Dau." title="WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-crowd.jpg"> </a> Students pack into the FCPA Theatre at Owens Community College for a standing only crowd for Mr. Dau.
        <br> 
        <i>THE BLADE/LORI KING</i> 
        <span class="right innertube blacktext tinytext bold"> <a href="/image/2015/02/25/800x_b1_cCM_z/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-crowd.jpg" rel="storyimage2" class="colorbox" title="Students pack into the FCPA Theatre at Owens Community College for a standing only crowd for Mr. Dau. THE BLADE/LORI KING">Enlarge</a> | <a href="http://toledoblade.mycapture.com/mycapture/remoteimage.asp?image=http%3A//www.toledoblade.com/image/2015/02/25/600x600_cCM_w1/WebPbg-GenocideTalk24-crowd.jpg&amp;Caption=Students%20pack%20into%20the%20FCPA%20Theatre%20at%20Owens%20Community%20College%20for%20a%20standing%20only%20crowd%20for%20Mr.%20Dau.&amp;BackText=Return%20to%20the%20Story&amp;backurl=http%3A//www.toledoblade.com/Our-Town-Home-Perrysburg/2015/02/25/South-Sudan-war-survivor-tells-of-horror-in-Owens-talk.html&amp;PhotographerID=8900" target="_blank"> Buy This Photo </a> </span> 
       </div> 
       <p>In 2001, he was resettle in Syracuse, N.Y., where he worked odd jobs, sometimes three or four at a time. Mr. Dau, who didn’t have any formal schooling until he arrived in Kenya at age of 17, earned an associate degree from Onondaga Community College in Syracuse and a bachelor's degree from Syracuse University. He believes that community colleges are essential to helping build strong communities.</p> 
       <p>“I love community college because it’s for everyone. Everyone gets in. You fit in,” Mr. Dau said.</p> 
       <p>Students said they found his talk inspiring and eye-opening.</p> 
       <p>“It was touching. It showed me that we’re spoiled and take things for granted,” said Mylena Sala, a pre-nursing student at Owens. “We times get tough, we have to keep pushing. I get lazy during the semester. Listening to everything he went through to survive, it’s amazing.”</p> 
       <p>Contact Blade staff writer RoNeisha Mullen at: rmullen@theblade.com or 419-343-3299.</p> 
      </div> 
